reviewText: This 1995 concert film at the Royal Albert Hall of the 10th anniversary of Les Miserables has great songs and spectacular performances by much of the original cast of the play. Clearly the so called stars of the 2013 mediocre film version (Jackman, Crowe, Hathaway, et al) can't hold a candle to these lesser known but far better actors/singers (Colm Wilkinson shines as Valjean, as does Philip Quast as Valjean, Michael Maguire as Enjolras, Ruthie Henstall as Fantine and Lea Salonga as Eponine). Most of the songs are terrific, but I loved the performances of "One Day More", "Do You hear the people sing", "I dreamed a dream", "Stars" and "ABC Cafe/Red and Black"

reviewText: I have seen the stage play and I have seen the movie (2012). They are both GREAT.  But if you want the best of both worlds...music and acting, this is a keepsake for all time. I've seen it many times on my own videotape, but this DVD is one to keep forever. The cast is in costume; nevertheless, they are also in concert, in front of microphones so you can hear every nuance of their spectacular voices--leads, supporting actors, and chorus. It is now newly remastered in 5.1 Surround Sound. The concert was given in 1995, at the Royal Albert Hall, with a full orchestra [Royal Philharmonic, I think] and chorus. I can't explain to you how moving this is . . . how sad . . . how uplifting . . . yes, and even funny (with Alun Armstrong as "Master of the 'Ouse!") Jean Valjean is sung by Colm Wilkinson, who created the role; his enemy, Javert, is sung by Philip Quast [his "This I Swear By the Stars" gives me goosebumps]; Eponine is sung by Lea Salonga, Tony-award winning actress for "Miss Saigon." There's no way I can give a "favorite voice" or even a "favorite song." The 2 most moving songs to me are "Bring Him Home" [as Valjean prays for Marius] and "Empty Chairs at Empty Tables" [as Michael Ball (Marius) grieves for his dead friends. How can I forget Fantine's (Ruthie Henshall) "I Dreamed a Dream?" Makes me cry every time.The ensemble thrills as it sings "One Day More" and the finale.  I received my copy today, along with an extra disc about the making of "Les Mis."  Cost & shipping? $23.97!!!  You will not regret ordering this. And I'm not going to tell you about the several surprises therein.  ENJOY.  Betty Willard.

reviewText: Other reviewers have pointed out some of issues with the current theatrical release, sacrificing in some cases musicality for acting.  I don't want to step into the debate over Jackman's and Crowe's singing ability.  However, *this* presentation doesn't sacrifice anything for anything.Musically it is outstanding!  Beyond the stellar performances by this "best-of-the-best" cast and RPO I really liked that the presentation contained small set pieces, including costumes and props, that capture the emotion of a stage performance.  On top of that, excellent camera work shows just how much a skilled actor can convey without elaborate sets, effects, or other ephemera.  For me, it provided the excitement of a live performance where everyone "lays it on the line" with just one take.While this DVD didn't replace seeing Les Mis on stage, or even on screen for that matter, it did provide a very powerful way to re-live, and perhaps amplify, the enjoyment I have already received.
summary: A breathtaking combination of a live concert and a dramatic performance

reviewText: This is the classic 10th Anniversary Concert Performance of Les Miserables, shot live at the Royal Albert Hall in 1995.  Though my favorite is the re-vamped 25th Anniversary production shot in 2010 at the O2 Arena, I have *cherished* this 10th anniversary concert perfomance since I first laid eyes and ears on it when it aired on PBS in February of 1996.  It is simply beautiful, a breathtaking concert performance.  I call it a tad "incomplete," because several important songs, "connective tissue" of the musical if you will, are left out of this performance but restored to the 25th anniversary production (such as Valjean's confession to Marius, and Valjean's reading of the letter that Marius wrote to Cosette the night of the barricade battle).  The omission of these songs is glaring after seeing the 25th Anniversary over and over.  But get past that:  get BOTH the 25th Anniversary for a more complete production but PLEASE DO NOT FAIL to get this 10th Anniversary Production as well.  If you don't get it, you will be missing out on some historic Les Mis vocal performances, such as Michael Ball wiith his beautiful and powerful voice performing the role of Marius, or an unforgettable performance by Philip Quast as Inspector Javert.  Ruthie Henshall, with her soft facial features, sweet smile, and beautiful voice, is a stunning Fantine.  And adorable LEA SALONGA is, in this 10th Anniversary, priceless as the giant-hearted EPONINE (while in the 2010 25th Anniversary, Lea returns, now playing the role of FANTINE!).  Please do yourselves a favor, get, and cherish, this precious 10th Anniversary performance of Les Miserables. It is such a treat for the eyes and, especially, the ears and heart.
summary: A *WONDERFUL* but a tad Incomplete, LES MIS' PERFORMANCE

reviewText: There are many versions of Les Miserable.  The 25th Anniversay; The 2013 movie with the cast of non-singers; and several CD versions.  To my mind the best performances by far are those in this 10th Anniversary edition.  The cast is without rivals for each of the major roles.  There are some singers with a prettier voice than Colm Wilkinson who have sung the Jean Valjean role.  But no one delivers better styling of the songs.  Lea Salonga delivers a spectacular performance of Eponine.  Michael Ball singing the role of Marius is magnificent...great voice and presence.  Michael Maguire looks like he invented the role of the leader of the rebels....very moving singing performance (Do you Hear the People Sing).  Phillip Quast as inspector Javert delivers a coup de force performance.  Tenth Anniversary is a 10 star rating if they could go that high.
summary: The Best Version of Les Miserable

reviewText: This concert performance features the full Royal Philharmonic Orchestra, a 50 voice backup chorus and the best combination of the cast members from the London and Broadway productions. On my big screen TV it made me feel like I was there as I listened to it with my surround sound stereo system. I had the best seat in the concert hall. The main characters were in their original costumes which enhanced the character and the presentation of each musical aspect of the concert. The power of song and music tell the best story and musical presentation ever written of the struggles of the common man/woman.This presentation is executed by top talent performers in every aspect. The raw emotions of the story reach out to your soul. The end result of this DVD is a spectacle that is one to remember. The DVD box comes with:* A collector's edition commemorative booklet* A replica ticket to the after show celebration at the Café Royal on Regent Street, London W1* Disk One is the concert in its entirety and it is 148 minutes long* Disk Two is the DVD Extras which covers the Creative process for the musical and a documentary titled Stage by Stage - The Making of Les MisérablesThe lead actors from all over the world who played the character of Jean Valjean sing at the end. This is a spectacular DVD and entertainment gift for anyone who likes musicals and top notch entertainment. BBC Home Entertainment has done a wonderful job in re-mastering this presentation and the 5.1 surround sound was just outstanding.This is an excellent gift for someone or even for you as a treat. You will enjoy it as it is a classic portrayed by the best talent available. I rate it 5 stars!I was supplied with a sample of this DVD for evaluation and I promised to provide a fair and honest review.

reviewText: I was going to say that the eagerly anticipated film version of "Les Miserables" had brought about a resurgence of interest in the long beloved musical.  But let's face it, that's simply not true.  Why?  Because "Les Miserables" has never faded from our minds, it is an enduring classic that simply refuses to slip into our memories.  In the last few months alone, I've seen Tom Hooper's film interpretation, re-watched the 25th Anniversary Concert on PBS, and enjoyed the re-release of this 10th Anniversary Concert DVD.  That's a lot of misery and heartbreak for one individual to endure!  Having seen various staged versions of the musical over the past twenty years, I must admit that initially it wasn't one of my favorites.  Okay, chastise me now.  But with time, I've come to appreciate the piece's intricate score (and stand-out songs) with more and more reverence upon different viewings.  And I am certainly now to be counted among the Les Mis fanatics!This concert was enacted in the Royal Albert Hall in 1995 and assembled original performers from both the London and Broadway productions.  Among the notable names, there is Colm Wilkinson, Ruthie Henshall, Lea Salonga, Michael Ball, and Judy Kuhn.  The staging provides a massive chorus (150+ voices) and the fantastic Royal Philharmonic Orchestra.  If you're a fan, I'm sure I don't have to sell the appeal of this concert!But what makes this version worth the investment?  There is a noticeable, and appreciated, sound upgrade as the concert has been remastered with 5.1 Surround Sound.  And I took full advantage, cranking it up and letting it fly!  Great stuff, powerfully performed.  This is a grand tribute concert!The DVD also has some great new Bonus features:1) The Creative Process: New interview footage with producer Cameron Mackintosh as well as the composer and lyricist.  This is not newly filmed, but newly released and gives an interesting archival angle.2) Stage by Stage: A great one hour 1988 British Documentary that I had seen before, but did not own.3) A replica invitation to a London after party after the musical's premiere and a nice 12 page commemorative booklet.  I like this cheesy (I mean collectible) stuff, but it's hardly essential.But the primary selling point is the concert itself.  And this DVD release did not disappoint.  KGHarris, 1/13.
summary: An Exemplary Tenth Anniversary Concert Receives A Noticeable (And Appreciated) Sound Upgrade

reviewText: I wasn't planning to watch this in one sitting. The concert itself, on disc 1 is 147 minutes long. I ended up watching most of it twice. Many parts brought tears to my eyes. It was that amazing. I was afraid that this DVD would be the orchestra and the 150 person chorus, dressed it suits and gowns, but the characters/singers were all in their original full show costumes and makeup. They interspersed scenes from the actual stage play every so often during the singing, so I had the feeling of seeing the stage play again. I watched this in our family room on a big screen TV with surround sound and was amazed at the sound and the quality of the performance. The DVD is 5.1 surround sound but keep in mind this is taking place on a stage in front of you, so most of the sound is coming from the front speakers and subwoofer.I've always loved the music from Les Miserables and the Royal Philharmonic Orchestra along with a 150 voice chorus and top stars from both the London and Broadway productions do an outstanding job. I sat glued to the screen, even though I've seen the live production in San Francisco many years ago and in smaller theater productions since. I have a few recordings of the soundtrack but having this DVD which is like a concert along with the scenes is a wonderful way to experience it again.The DVD includes a second disc with the making of Les Miserables, scene by scene and also interviews with the creators and producers telling about the creative process. There is a written program with a listing of the acts, songs, singers/actors and other details about what's happening in the different scenes. There is even a replica of a pass to an after show celebration at the Café Royal in London. I almost felt as if I were there.At the end, after all the standing ovations they have at least a dozen of the actors who played Jean Valjean from performances all over the world march up the main isle to the stage and join the cast. Each one sings a line from "Do You Hear the People Sing?" in their own language. It was one of the most moving parts on the DVD outside of the play itself. After that, and more standing ovations, there are fireworks and balloons and confetti dropped from above. It's quite spectacular. I had to watch that several times.I'm very grateful to have been supplied a sample copy of this DVD for review purposes from BBC Worldwide. I will be watching it many times in the coming months since this is one of my favorite musicals and this DVD is truly outstanding in its sound, presentation and performances.
summary: Wish I could give it 10 stars

reviewText: With the new feature film version now flooding theaters across the country, it was a perfect time for BB Home Video to reissue the 10th Anniversary Concert (held in 1995 at Royal Albert Hall). As you will see from  reviewer "Richard M"s review there were some minor "corrections" to the earlier release but the print has been newly remastered and will look great on any TV.The neat thing about the concert - which fills Disc One (bonuses are on Disc Two) - is that there are members of both the London and Broadway casts and they all have singing voices. (as opposed to the 2012 movie version which has actors not known for singing - doing just that.).My fellow reviewer - jjCeo - has already listed the detailed contents so I won't repeat those fact. I will say that if you just found Les Mis from the film version, you'll probably want this to see original cast members and see the bonus features, including the one- hour documentary on the "Making of Les Mis"I hope you found this review both informative and helpful.Steve Ramm"Anything Phonographic"
summary: Now that you've seen the Film, see (and hear) the original cast members and learn the backstory.
